	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I almost tried combofix, but the wording on their website would make one think it's more for a "trained professional" or something.
<br />
<br />I'd suggest using malwarebytes anti-malware - <a href="http://www.malwarebytes.org/" class="postlink">http://www.malwarebytes.org/</a>
<br />Quick scan, reboot, quickscan, reboot, repeat until it finds nothing.  I actually had a malware problem recently and this was the only program that seemed to be able to fix it.  And make sure it updates - it won't automatically.
<br />
<br />I don't think it can be prevented 100%, if a user allows something to run or gets hit with some kind of browser vulnerability, I think that's all it takes.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
